title: PowerShell Execution via Encoded Command Switch
id: 8f3e6b2a-1c4d-4a9e-9f7b-2d5c8e1a3f6b
status: experimental
description: >
  Detects PowerShell invoked with the -EncodedCommand switch (or any unambiguous
  abbreviation: -e, -en, -enc, -E, etc.), which passes a Base64/UTF-16LE-encoded
  script on the command line. This is a common technique used to obfuscate
  malicious commands from plaintext logging and simple string-matching defenses.
references:
  - https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/001/
  - https://github.com/redcanaryco/atomic-red-team/blob/master/atomics/T1059.001/T1059.001.md
author: Rahul Kumar Manthan
date: 2026-06-22
tags:
  - attack.execution
  - attack.t1059.001
logsource:
  category: process_creation
  product: windows
detection:
  selection_image:
    Image|endswith: '\powershell.exe'
  selection_encoded_switch:
    CommandLine|re: '(?i)\s-[e]{1}[a-z]{0,8}\s+[A-Za-z0-9+/=]{40,}'
  condition: selection_image and selection_encoded_switch
falsepositives:
  - Legitimate administrative scripts or scheduled tasks that pass encoded
    commands for line-length or character-escaping reasons (rare but possible
    in some enterprise automation tooling).
  - Splunk Universal Forwarder's own splunk-powershell.exe helper process,
    which is unrelated to this pattern but worth explicitly excluding via
    ParentImage if it ever appears with an encoded switch.
level: medium
